image.altText: A man of south Asian heritage in a blue suit, walking about of a courtroom

props.synopsis: A man accused of setting up a sham company used to steal $1.7 million from Australian scam victims has admitted in court to deleting crucial messages.

title.children: 'Where are they?': The bombshell text messages at the centre of a $1.7m scam fraud case

image.altText: Various people seen in a crowded suburb of Sydney

props.synopsis: Substantial discounts and sales saw Australians spending more on clothing and footwear in May. Although it may be good news for retailers, what does the increase in consumer spending mean for inflation and interest rates?

title.children: Sales season has us spending more during a cost-of-living crisis. Will we pay the price with higher interest rates?

image.altText: A split screen image of damage in Israel and a woman in southern Lebanon

props.synopsis: An Israeli town 1 kilometre from the Lebanon border is all but deserted as the threat of a new war looms. Inside Lebanon, residents are also preparing for a full-scale conflict.

title.children: On both sides of the Lebanon-Israel border, residents are bracing for a new war

image.altText: A man in a grey hoodie and cap looks at the camera.

props.synopsis: Jarrod Hawkins ran into the burning home in Sydney's West in the early hours of Sunday morning, and helped rescue four of the seven children inside.

title.children: Neighbour who ran into fire that killed three children calls on community to rally around family

image.altText: Generic photos of apartments, balconies

props.synopsis: Australian home values grew by 8 per cent in the past financial year. Here's a breakdown of how much you need to be earning to afford a property at the median value in your capital city.Â

title.children: Here's how much you need to earn to afford a mid-range home in your capital city

props.synopsis: A Russian missile barrage kills at least 20 and leaves 50 others injured in strikes on Kyiv and other Ukrainian cities, including a key children's hospital.

title.children: Children's hospital in Ukraine's capital one of many targets in Russian daytime missile attack

props.synopsis: A comprehensive audit will be conducted into all internet-facing technology used by Commonwealth agencies over rising concerns about foreign interference and influence threats.

title.children: Home Affairs boss orders government-wide sweep for foreign cyber threats

image.altText: A close-up of Emmanuel Macron

props.synopsis: France's government and new left-wing coalition found a way to stop the far-right National Rally party getting power. But forging a path through the country's political deadlock is a much-bigger challenge.Â

title.children: Macron's gamble foiled the far right, but threw France into political chaos

image.altText: Teenage boy works on laptop from a table in a cafe

props.synopsis: For almost half his life, Hamish has wanted to be nothing other than a computer coder. Now, in year 8, he is already getting started on a university degree to help him chase that dream.

title.children: Hamish, 13, learned computer coding from a YouTube tutorial. Now he's enrolled at university

image.altText: LNG tanker leaves Darwin Harbour.

props.synopsis: For an industry entering its sunset years, Australian gas certainly is attracting an enormous amount of attention and money. And yet, the local market is facing gas shortages, despite being one of the world's biggest exporters.

title.children: Why the global sharks are circling Australia's gas export industry once more

image.altText: Man clenches his fists

props.synopsis: Rather than move to give young Iranians more freedom, the Islamic Republic has become more hardline. Can Iran's new president, Masoud Pezeshkian, change that? And if not, the why did the regime allow him to run?

title.children: In Iranian elections, few candidates pass the strict vetting process. Why did new reformist president Masoud Pezeshkian pass the test?

image.altText: Jodie Comer and Austin Butler stand staring at the camera in 60s style clothes, his arm around her shoulders

props.synopsis: Drawing from a real-life photography book following the Chicago Outlaws, The Bikeriders follows the violence and drama of the period when outlaw motorcycle gangs went from hard-partying groups of outsiders to frightening organised crime groups.

title.children: Bruised and beautiful, bikie gang drama The Bikeriders will get your motor runnin'

image.altText: Butter on a wooden board

props.synopsis: With global butter prices at record highs, shoppers are hurting and Aussie dairy farmers look unlikely to cash in.

title.children: Australia is importing record amounts of butter at 'eye-watering' prices

image.altText: A young girl sits on a man's shoulders as he takes a selfie.

props.synopsis: The discovery of photos of Australian children in a gargantuan dataset being used to train leading AI models has given rise to a blame game and some divisive questions.Â

title.children: When photos of Australian kids are being used to train AI models, who is ultimately to blame?

image.altText: An empty street pictured at night lit up by street lights

props.synopsis: The Northern Territory police commissioner has declared a curfew in Alice Springs for three nights following a string of violent incidents in the outback town.

title.children: Snap three-night curfew declared in Alice Springs

image.altText: A single dingo lies down on sand

props.synopsis: DNA analysis suggests dingoes breed with other dogs less than previously thought and reveals key populations predate European colonisation.

title.children: Wild dog or dingo? Ancient DNA study suggests there's not much dog at all

image.altText: Satellite imagery of an ice shelf collapse.

props.synopsis: In 1968, an aircraft flew over the Larsen B ice shelf in Antarctica. More than six decades later, photos taken on that flight have been used to create a 3D model of the region's melting glaciers.

title.children: Melting glaciers in Antarctica have been digitally recreated using a trove of historical images

image.altText: Police officer walking on footpath and ambulance at scene of fatal Kingswood stabbing in Western Sydney

props.synopsis: Police have arrested a 22-year-old man after a woman was allegedly stabbed to death in Sydney's west in what they say is a domestic violence-related incident.

title.children: Woman stabbed to death in alleged domestic violence incident in Sydney's west

image.altText: woman sitting on camp chair in forest

props.synopsis: A 21-year-old woman who was involved in a protest that has disrupted passenger and coal trains in the Hunter has been sent to jail.

title.children: Protester sentenced to three months in jail for blocking country's biggest coal port

image.altText: Food waste piled up in a warehouse.

props.synopsis: According to the most recent UN Environment Programme Food Waste Index Report, about 28 per cent of food waste is from food services. Thai-developed app Yindii is fighting to lower that statistic.

title.children: Thai app helps reduce food waste and lower emissions

image.altText: The words 'Paramount Pictures' hung on a building.

props.synopsis: The deal represents the end of an era for Paramount, which has been owned by the Redstone family since Sumner Redstone turned a chain of theatres into a media empire.

title.children: Paramount Global and Skydance Media agree to merger in hopes of 'energising the business'

image.altText: A cockatoo bites the wire of the cage it is held in.

props.synopsis: Australian wildlife is showing up around the world where it shouldn't. Now animal forensics, artificial intelligence and advanced science are combining to combat the trafficking of these creatures.

title.children: Inside the battle to stop the $450 billion crime industry targeting Australia's wildlife

image.altText: A rainbow in a cloudy sky over an outback roadhouse

props.synopsis: Far west NSW graziers have renewed confidence in the condition of their livestock and country after a single rain event brought falls of up to 70 millimetres.

title.children: Outback graziers relieved after rain event fills dams and revives stock feed

image.altText: A man in a dark suit speaks at a podium

props.synopsis: French President Emmanuel Macron has decided to keep Gabriel Attal as prime minister after parliamentary elections in which the government's political camp lost its role as the strongest party to the left in a hung parliament.

title.children: France's Macron asks Attal to stay on as prime minister 'for the time being' to ensure 'stability'

image.altText: A man smiles during a rugby league team photo

props.synopsis: Even before he pulled on the jersey, Blues debutant Mitch Barnett made a serious sacrifice for his New South Wales teammates when he missed the birth of his second son in order to train alongside the team in the lead-up to Origin I.

title.children: Mitch Barnett missed the birth of his son to train with New South Wales. Now he'll make his State of Origin debut

image.altText: For lease signs in a window reflecting a tree

props.synopsis: Higher interest rates and rising rents are seeing a flood of calls and messages to the National Debt Hotline, mostly from younger people.

title.children: Financial stress 'through the roof' as interest rate hikes come home to roost

image.altText: A red, white and blue flag is held amongst a large group of people.

props.synopsis: In a pivotal run-off election in France, polling projections say a left-leaning coalition has won the most parliamentary seats, with President Emmanuel Macron's centrist alliance coming in second and the far right in third.

title.children: France shifts to the left, but risk of policy paralysis looms

image.altText: A woman with long dreadlocks, wearing a running leotard, pictured against a sunset and an athletics stadium.

props.synopsis: Australia is sending a 75-strong athletics team to the Paris Olympics, second only to the team that contested the Sydney Games on home soil and including both men's and women's 4x100m teams for the first time in 24 years.

title.children: Australia names largest-ever athletics team for a foreign Olympics ahead of Paris Games

image.altText: Two ancient roman busts, the man on the right has a speech bubble that says "knock knock"

props.synopsis: Professor Mary Beard, world-renowned classicist and author of Laughter in Ancient Rome, reveals what kind of jokes people were telling 2,000 years ago.

title.children: Think your dad's jokes are bad? Spare a thought for Julia, the daughter of Roman Emperor Augustus

image.altText: The Eiffel Tower lit up at night

props.synopsis: Australian Olympic officials have welcomed the partnership between the ABC and Nine, which will see key events broadcast live across the national broadcaster's regional radio network.

title.children: ABC Local Radio to bring Paris Olympic Games live across regional Australia

image.altText: A woman folding her arms in front of a vacant block of land

props.synopsis: The NSW government is accused of breaking an election promise by selling prime land in inner-city Sydney to private developers with no requirement for any social or affordable housing to be built.

title.children: Prime land close to Sydney CBD sold to developers with no requirement to build affordable housing

image.altText: A bag of heroin in an unidentifiable hand.

props.synopsis: Synthetic opioids like fentanyl and nitazenes are already finding their way into Australia's drug supply. Experts are concerned surges in the drug could have fatal consequences and are calling on the government to prepare.Â

title.children: Experts release plan to head off potentially fatal overdoses as fentanyl and nitazenes hit Victorian drug market
